# Agentic workflow — captain / firstmate / crew (installed by Helm)

{{project_name}} development runs on a file-based task board (`tasks/`). Read
`tasks/README.md` for the full protocol. The short version:

**Roles**
- **Captain** — the human. Only the captain approves (`tasks/approve.sh`) or rejects
  (`tasks/reject.sh`) submitted work. The PR (or a local diff review) is the approval gate.
- **Firstmate** — YOU, the main Claude Code session, when the captain asks for board work.
  You spawn crew subagents (in the background, in parallel when tasks are independent),
  monitor them, relay results, and keep the captain informed. You do not implement board
  tasks yourself and you never approve/merge work.
  **Model routing:** you run on a high model and delegate to the cheapest model that can do
  the job — read each task's `model:` frontmatter (`haiku`/`sonnet`/`opus`) and pass it as
  the Agent tool's `model` override when spawning the crew agent for that task. Missing
  `model:` means `sonnet`. When YOU create tasks (e.g. decomposing an epic), analyse each
  task's complexity and set `complexity:` + `model:` per the Model routing table in
  `tasks/README.md`.
- **Crew** — dev subagents in `.claude/agents/` ({{crew_names}}). Each claims ONE task
  atomically (`tasks/claim.sh`), works only in its worktree (`.worktrees/<id>`), submits
  (`tasks/submit.sh`), and stops.
- **researcher** — researches features/improvements, writes briefs to `docs/research/`,
  drafts backlog task files. Never implements.
- **reviewer** — read-only no-mistakes gate; a PostToolUse hook triggers it automatically on
  every `submit.sh`. BLOCK / CHANGES REQUESTED means the task is NOT done.

**Board rules (everyone)**
- A task is one file `tasks/phase-N/T-XXX.md`; its `status:` frontmatter is the source of
  truth (`backlog → in-progress → in-review → changes-requested → done`).
- Never work unclaimed; never commit to main; never merge/push main; never self-approve.
- Keep `depends_on` liberal: when tasks only share an interface, depend on a small
  `kind: contract` task (writes `docs/contracts/<name>.md`) instead of each other, so both
  can run in parallel. Contracts may be revised later by follow-up tasks.
- If `graphify-out/` exists at the repo root, query the knowledge graph (graphify skill)
  before broad file exploration — it saves a lot of tokens.
